{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778560625,"nonce":"VL8riIMVyrQfmpysuD1x9wY+698=","title":"Part of phase umbrella `f695729`. Follow-up from the `d448c9d` consultation synthesis (2026-05-11) — Tier 3 of the recommended path.","message":"Once Tier 2 (`66a3374`) has confirmed that the trained LTV regulator reproduces the analytical Riccati Δv on a matched objective, the question becomes: does the GRU give a different Δv signature than the linear regulator *under the same matched objective*? If yes, decoupling-via-architecture is the explanation for the +Δv vs ≈0 gap in synthesis.md §5.3. If no, the prior empirical gap was driven entirely by objective/adversary mismatch and the decoupling story dissolves.\n\n\nTrain a GRU controller with the **exact same** plant/cost/horizon/adversary/delay treatment as Tier 2's variant 1 (LTV regulator). Specifically:\n\n- Same plant parameters (mass, damping, motor filter, sensory delay)\n- Same horizon\n- Same Q schedule (`(t/N)^k` matched, normalised the same way)\n- Same R / control penalty\n- Same disturbance channel (must match the flavor that the linear regulator was matched against in 2.2)\n- **No** delayed-reach hold loss\n- **No** catch trials\n- **No** motor or sensory noise (unless they are part of the analytical setup being matched)\n- **No** `nn_output` / `nn_hidden` regularization\n\nThe result is *not* a faithful clone of how production GRUs are trained — it is a clean H∞ Riccati cost clone applied to a GRU. The production-faithful version remains the f47abb1 / flavor-B family.\n\n\n\nEither a new script (`scripts/train_matched_objective_gru.py`) or a CLI mode of `train_minimax.py` that strips the auxiliary losses. Reuse the Tier 2 task setup (fixed direction, one start, one target).\n\n\nSame n_replicates as Tier 2 (so the cross-architecture Δv comparison is paired). Compute the Pareto diagnostic (nominal peak velocity vs robustness metric) the same way as Tier 2.\n\n\nSide-by-side plot of LTV-regulator Pareto curve and GRU Pareto curve. Reported quantities:\n\n- Δv signature for each architecture\n- K_local norm at γ near γ* (use the Tier 1.1 affine-decomposition machinery if available)\n- u_0(t) profile shift between baseline and adversarial within each architecture\n- Bimodality structure (do GRU replicates split, does the linear regulator?)\n\n\n- **GRU Δv ≈ 0 while linear Δv \u003e 0 under matched objective**: decoupling-via-architecture is real and the regulator-vs-tracker framing survives. Proceed to Tier 4 or above (richer tracker, x_nom representation analysis).\n- **Both architectures give Δv \u003e 0 under matched objective**: the empirical gap in synthesis.md §5.3 was driven by objective mismatch (extra losses, noise, catch trials), not architecture. Decoupling-via-architecture is not supported. Pivot to objective-design as the live question.\n- **GRU still shows bimodality**: cluster the replicates (per Tier 1.2 `0c95d6b`) and report each basin separately. The H∞-like basin under matched objective is more interpretable than the average.\n\n\n- Tier 2 (`66a3374`) — the matched-objective Riccati round-trip must close before this tier is meaningful. Without that calibration, a GRU vs linear comparison is uninterpretable.\n- Tier 1.1 (`0c95d6b`) — the affine-decomposition machinery feeds 3.3.\n\n\n- Parent: `d448c9d` (decoupling acid test)\n- Umbrella: `f695729` (regulator-coupling phase)\n- Sibling tiers: Tier 1 `0c95d6b`, Tier 2 `66a3374`\n- Consultation: `results/d448c9d/consultations/2026-05-11_decoupling_framing/`\n- Training-methods coord: `c99ad9d` (clean H∞ clone is a training-method recipe)","files":null}]}